<module status="bronze">
  <h>toponymic name-descriptions</h>
  <p>Toponymic name-descriptions are <a href="?xx=nouns/name_descriptions">name-descriptions</a>
    which are also <a href="?xx=nouns/toponyms">toponyms</a>, i.e. they are definite common noun
    phrases used to name places and other geographical entities.</p>
  <section id="deps">
    <h>dependents</h>
    <p>Like other name-descriptions, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified into two
      grammatical types – <ul>
        <li><emph>pre-specified</emph> toponymic name-descriptions, e.g. <g>An t-Eilean Dubh</g>
          <en>The Black Isle</en>, <g>A’ Chomraich</g>
          <en>Applecross</en>, <g>An Fhraing</g>
          <en>France</en>, <g>Na h-Ìnnseachan</g>
          <en>India</en>, <g>Am Monadh Ruadh</g>
          <en>The Cairngorms</en>, <g>An Linne Latharnach</g>
          <en>The Lorne Firth</en>, <!--<a href="?gd=manachainn"><g>A’ Mhanachainn</g></a>-->
          <g>A’ Mhanachainn</g>
          <en>Beauly</en>.</li>
        <li><emph>post-specified</emph> toponymic name-descriptions, e.g. <g>Eilean nam Muc</g>
          <en>Muck</en>, <g>Baile Ùr an t-Slèibhe</g>
          <en>Newtonmore</en>, <g>Dùthaich MhicAoidh</g>
          <en>North Sutherland</en>, <g>Innis Tìle</g>
          <en>Iceland</en>, <g>Beinn a’ Bhreacaidh</g>
          <en>Ben Vrackie</en>, <g>Loch Obha</g>
          <en>Loch Awe</en>, <!--<a href="?gd=Eaglais_nam_Manach_Liatha"><g>Eaglais nam Manach
              Liath(a)</g></a>--><g>Eaglais nam Manach Liath(a)</g>
          <en>Greyfriars Kirk</en>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>
  <section id="uses">
    <h>uses</h>
    <p>Like other toponyms, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified semantically according to
      the kind of geographical entity they refer to – <ul>
        <li>islands and districts, e.g. <g>An t-Eilean Dubh</g>, <g>Eilean nam Muc</g>, <g>Dùthaich
            MhicAoidh</g>
          <!--<boxlink ref="#districts"/>--></li>
        <li>towns and settlements, e.g. <g>A’ Chomraich</g>, <g>Baile Ùr an t-Slèibhe</g>
          <!--<boxlink ref="#settlements"/>--></li>
        <li>countries and continents, e.g. <g>An Fhraing</g>, <g>Na h-Ìnnseachan</g>, <g>Innis
            Tìle</g>
          <!--<boxlink ref="#countries"/>--></li>
        <li>mountains and uplands, e.g. <g>Beinn a’ Bhreacaidh</g>, <g>Am Monadh Ruadh</g></li>
        <li>rivers, lakes and seas, e.g. <g>An Linne Latharnach</g>, <g>Loch Obha</g>
          <!--<boxlink ref="#water"/>--></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>



  <section id="lenition">
    <h>lenition</h>
    <p>The head (i.e. initial) noun in a (post-specified) toponymic name-description which is itself
      the (genitive) (post-)specifier of another noun seems to be traditionally not lenited – <ul>
        <li><g>mullach <emph>B</emph>einn Nibheis</g>
          <en>the summit of Ben Nevis</en></li>
        <li><g>mòr-thubaist <emph>Dr</emph>ochaid Thatha</g>
          <en>the Tay Bridge disaster</en></li>
        <li><g>Comhairle <emph>S</emph>iorrachd Pheairt</g>
          <en>Perthshire Council</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>However, when the toponymic name-description denotes a town or city, it is often lenited – <ul>
        <li><g>muinntir <emph>Dh</emph>ùn Èideann</g>
          <en>the people of Edinburgh</en></li>
        <li><g>aiseag <emph>Bh</emph>aile a’ Chaolais</g>
          <en>the Ballachulish ferry</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>In addition, lenition of toponymic name-descriptions is more frequent in modern Gaelic usage
      than in traditional usage, possibly influenced by Standard Irish – <ul>
        <li><g>mullach <emph>Bh</emph>einn Nibheis</g>
          <en>the summit of Ben Nevis</en></li>
        <li><g>mòr-thubaist <emph>Dhr</emph>ochaid T[h]atha</g>
          <en>the Tay Bridge disaster</en></li>
        <li><g>Comhairle <emph>Sh</emph>iorrachd Pheairt</g>
          <en>Perthshire Council</en></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </section>





